\p

\c 21
\p
\v 1 Now {there} was a famine in the days of David three years, year after year. And David sought the face of Yahweh, and Yahweh said, “To Saul and to the house {is} blood, because he killed the Gibeonites.”

\ts\*
\p
\v 2 And the king called to the Gibeonites, and he spoke to them. (Now the Gibeonites {were} not from the sons of Israel. Rather, they {were} from the remnant of the Amorite. And the sons of Israel had sworn to them, but Saul sought to strike them when he was jealous for the sons of Israel and Judah.)
\v 3 And David said to the Gibeonites, “What shall I do for you, and with what shall I atone, then bless the inheritance of Yahweh?”

\ts\*
\p
\v 4 And the Gibeonites said to him, “{There is} no silver or gold for us with Saul or with his house. And {there is} not for us a man to kill in Israel.”

\ts\*
\p
And he said, “What are you saying I shall do for you?”

\ts\*
\p
\v 5 And they said to the king, “The man who ended us and who intended against us {that} we should be destroyed from stationing ourselves in all of the border of Israel,
\v 6 let seven men from his sons be given to us, and we will hang them before Yahweh at Gibeah of Saul, the chosen of Yahweh.”

\ts\*
\p
And the king said, “I, I will give.”

\ts\*
\p
\v 7 Now the king had compassion on Mephibosheth, the son of Jonathan, the son of Saul, because of the oath of Yahweh that {was} between them, between David and between Jonathan, the son of Saul.
\v 8 But the king took two of the sons of Rizpah, the daughter of Aiah, whom she bore to Saul, Armoni and Mephibosheth, and five of the sons of Michal, the daughter of Saul, whom she bore to Adriel, the son of Barzillai the Meholathite.
\v 9 And he gave them into the hand of the Gibeonites, and they hanged them on the hill to the face of Yahweh, and the seven of them fell together. And they, they were killed in the days of the harvest, in the first {days}, at the beginning of the harvest of barley.

\ts\*
\p
\v 10 And Rizpah, the daughter of Aiah, took sackcloth, and she spread it for herself against a rock, from the beginning of the harvest until water was poured on them from the heavens. And she did not allow a bird of the heavens to rest on them by day or a beast of the field by night.
\v 11 And it was declared to David what Rizpah, the daughter of Aiah, the concubine of Saul, had done.

\ts\*
\p
\v 12 And David went, and he took the bones of Saul and the bones of Jonathan his son from the lords of Jabesh Gilead, who had stolen them from the open area of Beth Shan, where the Philistines had hanged them there on the day the Philistines struck Saul at Gilboa.
\v 13 And he brought up from there the bones of Saul and the bones of Jonathan his son, and they gathered the bones of the hanged ones.

\ts\*
\p
\v 14 And they buried the bones of Saul and Jonathan his son in the land of Benjamin, in Zela, in the tomb of Kish his father. And they did all that the king commanded. And God was entreated for the land after this.

\ts\*
\p
\v 15 Now war was to the Philistines again with Israel. And David went down, and his servants with him, and they fought the Philistines. And David wearied.
\v 16 And Ishbi Benob, who {was} among the children of Rapha, and the weight of his spear {was} 300 {shekels} of bronze in weight, and he was girded {with} a new {weapon}, and he said to strike David.
\v 17 But Abishai, the son of Zeruiah, helped him, and he struck the Philistine, and he killed him. Then the men of David adjured him, saying, “You shall not go out with us to battle anymore, so you do not extinguish the lamp of Israel.”

\ts\*
\p
\v 18 And it happened after this that {there} was a battle again with the Philistines, at Gob. Then Sibbecai the Hushathite struck Saph, who {was} among the children of Rapha.

\ts\*
\p
\v 19 And {there} was battle again with the Philistines at Gob. And Elhanan, the son of Jaare Oregim the Bethlehemite, struck Goliath the Gittite, and the wood of his spear {was} like the beam of weavers.

\ts\*
\p
\v 20 And {there} was battle again at Gath, and {there} was a man of stature, and the digits of his hands and the digits of his feet {were} six and six, 24 {in} number. And he also was born to Rapha.
\v 21 And he taunted Israel, and Jonathan, the son of Shimeah, the brother of David, struck him.

\ts\*
\p
\v 22 These four were born to Rapha in Gath. And they fell by the hand of David and by the hand of his servants.

\ts\*
\p

\c 22
\p
\v 1 And David spoke to Yahweh the words of this song on the day Yahweh delivered him from the palm of all of his enemies and from the palm of Saul.
\v 2 And he said, “Yahweh {is} my rock and my stronghold and my deliverer, mine.
\v 3 God of my rock, I take refuge in him, my shield and the horn of my salvation, my stronghold and my refuge, my savior, you save me from violence.

\ts\*
\p
\v 4 {To} the one being praised I call, {to} Yahweh, and I am saved from my enemies.
\v 5 For the waves of death surrounded me, the torrents of wickedness terrified me.
\v 6 The cords of Sheol surrounded me, the snares of death confronted me.

\ts\*
\p
\v 7 In my distress I called {to} Yahweh, and to my God I called. And he heard my voice from his temple, and my cry {was} in his ears.
\v 8 Then the earth shook and trembled. The foundations of the heavens quaked and shook themselves, because it burned to him.
\v 9 Smoke went up from his nose, and fire from his mouth devoured. Coals from him burned.
\v 10 And he lowered the heavens, and he came down, and a dark cloud {was} under his feet.
\v 11 And he rode on a cherub, and he flew. He was seen on the wings of the wind.
\v 12 And he set darkness, the booths around him {were} a gathering of waters, clouds of the skies.
\v 13 From the brightness before him, coals of fire burned.
\v 14 Yahweh thundered from the heavens, the Most High uttered his voice.
\v 15 And he sent out arrows, and he scattered them, lightning, and he panicked them.
\v 16 And the valleys of the sea were seen, the foundations of the world were uncovered, at the rebuke of Yahweh, from the blast of the breath of his nose.

\ts\*
\p
\v 17 He stretched out from the height, he took hold of me. He drew me out of many waters.
\v 18 He delivered me from my strong enemy, from the ones hating me, for they were stronger than me.
\v 19 They confronted me on the day of my calamity, but Yahweh was my support.
\v 20 And he brought me out to an open space.

\ts\*
\p
He delivered me because he delighted in me.
\v 21 Yahweh has rewarded me according to my righteousness. According to the cleanness of my hands, he has given back to me.
\v 22 For I have kept the ways of Yahweh, and I have not been wicked from my God.
\v 23 For all of his judgments {are} before me, and his statutes, I have not turned away from them.
\v 24 And I have been blameless toward him, and I have kept myself from my iniquity.
\v 25 And Yahweh has given back to me according to my righteousness, according to my cleanness before his eyes.

\ts\*
\p
\v 26 To the faithful you show yourself faithful; with the mighty blameless, you show yourself blameless.
\v 27 With the purified, you show yourself pure, but with the crooked, you show yourself cunning.
\v 28 And you save a lowly people, but your eyes {are} against the ones being high, you bring {them} down.

\ts\*
\p
\v 29 For you {are} my lamp, Yahweh, and Yahweh lightens my darkness.
\v 30 For by you, I run {after} a troop.

\ts\*
\p
By my God, I leap {over} a wall.
\v 31 This God, his way {is} perfect. The word of Yahweh is refined. He {is} a shield to all of the ones taking refuge in him.
\v 32 For who {is} God except Yahweh? And who {is} a rock except our God?
\v 33 This God {is} my fortress of strength, and he makes my way perfect,
\v 34 making my feet like a deer, and he makes me stand on my high places,
\v 35 training my hands for war, and my arms bend a bow of bronze.
\v 36 And you give to me the shield of your salvation, and your answer makes me great.
\v 37 You enlarge my step under me, and my feet do not slip.

\ts\*
\p
\v 38 I pursue my enemies, and I destroy them, and I do not return until I have ended them.
\v 39 And I devour them, and I shatter them, and they do not arise, but they fall under my feet.
\v 40 And you gird me {with} valor for war; you make the ones rising up under me bow down.
\v 41 And my enemies, you give to me the back of {their} neck; the ones hating me, and I destroy them.
\v 42 They look, but {there is} no one saving; to Yahweh, but he does not answer them.
\v 43 And I beat them like the dust of the earth.

\ts\*
\p
Like the mud of the streets, I pulverize them, I stomp them.
\v 44 And you rescue me from the disputes of my people. You keep me as the head of nations. People I did not know serve me.
\v 45 Sons of the foreigner come cringing to me. At the hearing of an ear, they hear me.
\v 46 Sons of the foreigner fade away, and they come trembling from their fortresses.

\ts\*
\p
\v 47 Yahweh {is} alive! And blessed {be} my rock, and may the God of the rock of my salvation be exalted,
\v 48 the God giving vengeance to me and bringing down peoples under me
\v 49 and bringing me out from my enemies.

\ts\*
\p
And from the ones arising {against} me, you lift me up; from a man of violences, you deliver me.
\v 50 Therefore I thank you, Yahweh, among the nations, and I sing praise to your name,
\v 51 the one magnifying the salvation of his king and doing covenant faithfulness to his anointed, to David, and to his seed until forever.”

\ts\*
\p

\c 23
\p
\v 1 Now these {are} the last words of David. An oracle of David the son of Jesse, and an oracle of the man raised {to} height, the anointed of the God of Jacob, and the delightful {one} of the songs of Israel.

\ts\*
\p
\v 2 “The Spirit of Yahweh spoke by me, and his word {was} on my tongue.
\v 3 The God of Israel spoke to me, the Rock of Israel said, ‘A righteous one ruling over man {is} ruling {in} the fear of God,
\v 4 and {is} like the light of morning, {when} the sun rises, a morning {with} no clouds, {like} grass from the earth from brightness after rain.’

\ts\*
\p
\v 5 For {is} not my house thus with God? For he has made a covenant with me forever, ordered in everything and secured. For all my salvation and every desire, surely will he not make {it} sprout?
\v 6 But the wicked, all of them, {will be} like a thorn thrown away because they do not take in the hand.
\v 7 But the man {who} touches them will be filled {with} iron or the wood of a spear. And burning, they will be burned in the fire in place.”

\ts\*
\p
\v 8 These {are} the names of the warriors who {were} to David. Josheb Basshebeth the Tahchemonite {was} the head of the Three. He was lifting his spear against 800, slain at one time.

\ts\*
\p
\v 9 And after him {was} Eleazar the son of Dodo, the son of Ahohi, among the three warriors with David. When they taunted the Philistines, they had gathered themselves there for battle, and the men of Israel went up,
\v 10 he, he arose and struck the Philistines until his hand tired and his hand clung to the sword. And Yahweh did great salvation on that day, and the people returned after him only to plunder.

\ts\*
\p
\v 11 And after him {was} Shammah, the son of Agee the Hararite. Now the Philistines gathered themselves to Lehi, and a portion of the field there was full {of} lentils, and the people fled from the face of the Philistines.
\v 12 But he stationed himself in the midst of the portion, and he delivered it, and he struck the Philistines. And Yahweh did great salvation.

\ts\*
\p
\v 13 And three from the head Thirty went down, and they came to the harvest, to David, to the cave of Adullam. And a troop of Philistines was camping in the Valley of the Raphaites.
\v 14 And David {was} then in the stronghold, and a garrison of the Philistines {was} then {in} Bethlehem.
\v 15 And David desired, and he said, “Who will give me water to drink from the well of Bethlehem that {is} at the gate?”
\v 16 And the three warriors broke through the camp of the Philistines, and they drew water from the well of Bethlehem that {is} at the gate. And they carried {it} away and brought {it} to David. But he was not willing to drink it, and he poured it out to Yahweh.
\v 17 And he said, “Profane to me, Yahweh, from my doing this, the blood of the men having gone with their lives!” And he was not willing to drink it.

\ts\*
\p  These {things} the three warriors did.

\ts\*
\p
\v 18 And Abishai, the brother of Joab, the son of Zeruiah, he {was} the head of the three, and he was lifting his spear against 300, slain. And to him {was} a name among the Three.
\v 19 {Is it not} that he was the most honored of the three? And he became to them a commander. But he did not come to the Three.

\ts\*
\p
\v 20 And Benaiah, the son of Jehoiada, {was} a son of a man of valor, many deeds, from Kabzeel. He, he struck the two Ariel of Moab. And he, he went down and struck a lion in the midst of the pit on a day of snow.
\v 21 And he himself struck a man of Egypt, a man of appearance. Now in the hand of the Egyptian {was} a spear, and he went down against him with a staff. But he seized the spear from the hand of the Egyptian, and he killed him with his spear.
\v 22 These {things}, Benaiah, the son of Jehoiada did. And to him {was} a name among the three warriors.
\v 23 More than the Thirty, he was honored, but to the Three, he did not come.

\ts\*
\p
And David put him to his bodyguard.
\v 24 Asahel the brother of Joab {was} among the Thirty; Elhanan, the son of Dodo {of} Bethlehem;
\v 25 Shammah the Harodite; Elika the Harodite;
\v 26 Helez the Paltite; Ira, the son of Ikkesh the Tekoite;
\v 27 Abiezer the Anathothite; Mebunnai the Hushathite;
